      "story": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 1,
          "text": "Neutron Stars: Matter at the Edge of Collapse",
          "id": "title",
          "style": "title",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "How the violent death of a massive star can leave behind an object the size of a city and as dense as the nucleus of an atom.",
          "style": "subtitle"
        },
        {
          "type": "spacer",
          "height": "6pt"
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "The Death That Leaves a Heart Behind",
          "id": "formation",
          "style": "h2",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "A star many times heavier than the Sun does not end its life gently. For millions of years it fuses hydrogen into helium, helium into carbon, and onward through ever-heavier elements, wrapping itself in concentric shells like the layers of an onion. But this chain of fusion halts abruptly at iron. Forging elements heavier than iron consumes energy instead of releasing it, so the moment the core becomes iron, the furnace that has held the star against its own gravity simply goes out.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "spans": [
            {
              "text": "What follows is among the most violent events in the cosmos. Stripped of pressure support, the iron core — already heavier than the Sun yet smaller than the Earth — collapses in a fraction of a second. Protons and electrons are crushed together into neutrons, unleashing a torrent of ghostly particles called "
            },
            {
              "text": "neutrinos",
              "style": "em"
            },
            {
              "text": ". The infalling envelope slams into the suddenly rigid neutron core, rebounds, and the star detonates as a "
            },
            {
              "text": "core-collapse supernova",
              "style": "term"
            },
            {
              "text": " that can briefly outshine its entire host galaxy."
            }
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The whole sequence unfolds with breathtaking speed:",
          "style": "body",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "ordered": true,
          "items": [
            "A star born with more than roughly eight times the Sun's mass burns its way up to an inert iron core.",
            "Iron cannot yield energy through fusion, so pressure support at the centre collapses.",
            "In well under a second the core implodes, fusing electrons and protons into neutrons.",
            "Neutron degeneracy pressure, reinforced by the strong nuclear force, abruptly arrests the fall.",
            "The rebound and a flood of neutrinos blow the outer layers off in a supernova.",
            "The exposed core survives as a neutron star — or, if it is heavy enough, as a black hole."
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "What remains at the centre is a neutron star: a sphere of almost pure neutrons holding one to two times the mass of the Sun inside a ball little more than twenty kilometres across.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "spacer",
          "height": "8pt"
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "A Spoonful Weighing a Billion Tonnes",
          "id": "structure",
          "style": "h2",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Density is the quality that sets a neutron star apart from anything in ordinary experience. Compressing the mass of the Sun into the volume of a small city pushes matter to roughly the density of an atomic nucleus — several hundred trillion times denser than water. A single teaspoon of neutron-star material would weigh about as much as a mountain range.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Yet a neutron star is far from a featureless blob. Gravity and nuclear forces sort it into distinct layers. A wafer-thin atmosphere of hot plasma sits atop a solid crust of ions locked in a crystalline lattice. Deeper down, nuclei grow so neutron-rich that neutrons begin to drip out of them, and the matter contorts into exotic shapes nicknamed ‘nuclear pasta.’ Below the crust lies a vast core of superfluid neutrons, and at the very centre — at densities beyond anything physics has pinned down — matter may dissolve into free quarks or other states no laboratory has produced.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "figure",
          "object": {
            "type": "group",
            "id": "ns_cutaway",
            "bind": "ns",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "ellipse",
                "id": "crust",
