          "caption": "Schematic interior of a neutron star, from crust to core (not to scale).",
          "align": "center",
          "break_before": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "These conditions translate into figures with no terrestrial parallel:",
          "style": "body",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "header": [
            {
              "content": "Property",
              "style": "th"
            },
            {
              "content": "Typical neutron star",
              "style": "th"
            },
            {
              "content": "Everyday comparison",
              "style": "th"
            }
          ],
          "columns": [
            {
              "width": "26%",
              "align": "left"
            },
            {
              "width": "40%",
              "align": "left"
            },
            {
              "width": "34%",
              "align": "left"
            }
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "Mass",
              "≈ 1.4 – 2.1 M☉",
              "Up to about twice the Sun"
            ],
            [
              "Radius",
              "≈ 10 – 13 km",
              "The size of a city"
            ],
            [
              "Mean density",
              "≈ 4 × 10¹⁷ kg/m³",
              "The density of an atomic nucleus"
            ],
            [
              "Surface gravity",
              "≈ 2 × 10¹¹ g",
              "Two hundred billion times Earth's pull"
            ],
            [
              "Fastest spin",
              "up to ≈ 700 turns per second",
              "Faster than a kitchen blender"
            ],
            [
              "Magnetic field",
              "10⁸ – 10¹⁵ gauss",
              "The strongest fields known in nature"
            ]
          ],
          "header_height": "22pt",
          "row_height": "20pt",
          "zebra": true,
          "cell_padding": [
            6,
            8,
            6,
            8
          ],
          "break_before": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "spans": [
            {
              "text": "The precise way matter behaves at these densities — its "
            },
            {
              "text": "equation of state",
              "style": "em"
            },
            {
              "text": " — is one of the great unsolved problems of modern physics. Because such conditions cannot be reproduced on Earth, neutron stars themselves serve as the only available laboratory."
            }
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "spacer",
          "height": "8pt"
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Cosmic Lighthouses",
          "id": "pulsars",
          "style": "h2",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Collapse does more than compress a star; it spins it up. Just as a figure skater turns faster when she pulls in her arms, a stellar core that shrinks from the breadth of the Sun to a few kilometres must conserve its angular momentum, and so it whirls — some young neutron stars rotating hundreds of times every second.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The collapse concentrates the star's magnetic field as fiercely as its spin, amplifying it to trillions of times the strength of any magnet built by human hands. A spinning magnet radiates, and a neutron star beams energy from its magnetic poles in two narrow cones. If one of those beams happens to sweep across the Earth, we see a pulse with every rotation — as regular as a ticking clock.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "block",
          "fill": "callout_bg",
          "padding": [
            14,
            16,
            14,
            16
          ],
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "Little Green Men, 1967",
              "style": "callout_title",
              "break_after": "avoid"
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "When Jocelyn Bell Burnell first recorded a string of impossibly regular pulses on her radio telescope, the signal was so precise that the source was half-jokingly labelled ‘LGM-1’, for Little Green Men. The pulses turned out to be natural: the lighthouse beam of a rotating neutron star, the first pulsar ever found.",
              "style": "callout_body"
            }
          ],
          "stroke_style": "callout_edge"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "These beaming neutron stars, or pulsars, come in a remarkable variety:",
          "style": "body",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "ordered": false,
          "marker": "•",
          "items": [
            [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "spans": [
                  {
                    "text": "Radio pulsars",
                    "style": "term"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " sweep lighthouse beams of radio waves across space with metronomic regularity, and serve as some of the most precise clocks in the universe."
                  }
                ],
                "style": "li_body"
              }
            ],
            [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "spans": [
                  {
                    "text": "Millisecond pulsars",
                    "style": "term"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " have been ‘recycled’ — spun up to hundreds of rotations per second by matter stripped from a companion star."
                  }
                ],
                "style": "li_body"
              }
            ],
            [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "spans": [
                  {
                    "text": "Magnetars",
                    "style": "term"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " carry the most intense magnetic fields known, occasionally convulsing in titanic bursts of X-rays and gamma rays."
                  }
                ],
                "style": "li_body"
              }
            ],
            [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "spans": [
                  {
                    "text": "X-ray binaries",
                    "style": "term"
                  },
                  {
                    "text": " blaze in X-rays as gas torn from an orbiting star spirals down and crashes onto the neutron star's surface."
                  }
                ],
                "style": "li_body"
              }
            ]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "spacer",
          "height": "8pt"
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Laboratories at the Edge of Physics",
          "id": "labs",
          "style": "h2",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Precisely because their interiors lie so far beyond our reach, neutron stars have become indispensable instruments for testing the laws of nature. Their fierce gravity bends light and slows time in ways that confirm Einstein's general relativity to extraordinary precision, and the steady drumbeat of pulsars lets astronomers weigh distant stars and hunt for ripples in spacetime itself.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "spans": [
            {
              "text": "In 2017 the field reached a milestone when two neutron stars, locked in a death spiral, were observed merging — first as a chirp of gravitational waves and moments later as a blaze of light. The collision flung out a cloud of debris glowing as a "
            },
            {
              "text": "kilonova",
              "style": "em"
            },
            {
              "text": ", and within it astronomers watched heavy elements being forged in real time."
            }
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "block",
          "fill": "callout2_bg",
          "padding": [
            14,
            16,
            14,
            16
          ],
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "Where Your Gold Came From",
              "style": "callout2_title",
              "break_after": "avoid"
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "The merger of 2017 helped settle a long-standing mystery: where the universe's heaviest elements are made. The wreckage of colliding neutron stars is now thought to be a principal forge of gold, platinum, and other heavy metals. Much of the gold in any wedding ring was very likely born in such a cataclysm.",
              "style": "callout_body"
            }
          ],
          "stroke_style": "callout2_edge"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Individual neutron stars push the science further still. The discovery of pulsars weighing about two solar masses sets hard limits on how squeezable ultra-dense matter can be, while X-ray observatories measuring the size of a neutron star to within a kilometre are steadily narrowing down the elusive equation of state.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "spacer",
          "height": "8pt"
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "The Edge of Collapse",
          "id": "limit",
          "style": "h2",
          "break_after": "avoid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "spans": [
            {
              "text": "There is, however, a ceiling. Above a critical mass — the "
            },
            {
              "text": "Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff limit",
              "style": "term"
            },
            {
              "text": ", somewhere near two and a quarter times the mass of the Sun — not even the defiance of densely packed neutrons can withstand gravity. Cross that threshold and collapse resumes without end, and the neutron star vanishes behind the horizon of a black hole."
            }
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "A neutron star therefore occupies a razor's edge in the story of matter: the densest object that can still hold itself up, poised one step short of oblivion. In its impossible interior, in its clockwork beams, and in the golden debris of its collisions, it remains one of the most extreme and instructive objects the universe has to offer.",
          "style": "body"
        }
      ],
